Professor Williams¶

Milestone 1

Market Analysis

¶

The purpose of this analysis is to research market data. I will gather data from several sources. The goal is to analyze the effect of economic data on stock performance. I will also use the S&P 500 as the benchmark for my stock performance. The sources of my data will come from various sources. I will pull the stock data from FMP a stock price API. The web address for FMP is Documentation V2 - API Reference | FMP. The economic data will come from the FRED. The FRED is managed by the St. louis Fed. The web address is Federal Reserve Economic Data | FRED | St. Louis Fed. Finally, I will pull S&P data from Wikipedia. The web address is S&P 500 - Wikipedia. Economic data will show a relationship between the stock data and the economy. And the S&P will show the relationship between the stock index and the market.
The plan for my analysis will be to add the different data sets into one data frame. I will run an exploratory analysis on the data. I will need to transform the data and determine the variables that make the greatest impact on the analysis. It will be important for me to build graphs to determine the connection between the variables. After I build my charts, I can run a regression analysis and test my model. For the regression analysis I will need to split my data into a training and a testing set. Along with any analysis there are challenges that I will have to manage.

Some challenges that I can foresee are issues with combining the different data sets. Since I am working with data sets from multiple sources, I’ll have to make sure they are formatted appropriately. There may also be problems with loading the data into the program. The data will be stored in different formats, so I’ll have to ensure that they are formatted in a manner that is compatible across data sets. Another challenge that I can anticipate is overfitting the data. I need to make that the training and testing sets are not in danger of overfitting the data.

Ethical concerns are always a factor when manipulating data. It is important to implement safeguards to prevent ethical. One ethical concern is the misrepresentation of the data. It is important that I don’t allow the data to misrepresent the results. Another ethical issue is bias. It’s important that I don’t allow my personal bias to cause me to see relationships that don’t exist.

In [4]:
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
  1. Prep the flat files

The next series of code loads the data from the FRED. I will use three data sets for my analysis. The first data set is the Coincident Economic Activity Index. This index measures the US economic condition. It takes into account non-farm payroll employment, the unemployment rate, average hours worked in manufacturing, and wages and salaries. The second data set is the Consumer Price Index. This measures the price changes of goods and services and is a leading indicator of inflation. The final data set from the FRED is the One Year T-Bill. Fluctuations in T-Bill rates indicate direction of the US Monetary Policy.

In [5]:
# This code loads in the cea data, creates a pandas dataframe, and displays the first 5 rows.
cea = pd.read_csv(r"coincident economic activity index.csv")
cea = pd.DataFrame(cea)

The next step is to combine the three data frames into one. This will give me the opportunity to do further analysis. The following series of codes will prep and combine the three data frames.

In [8]:
# The first line of code will store all three data frames into one object.
dfs = (cea, cpi, t_bill)
In [9]:
# The second line of code combines all the data into one new data frame.
new_data = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on = "observation_date", how = "outer"),dfs)
In [10]:
# The third line of code renames the columns in the data frame and displays the completed data frame.
new_data = new_data.set_axis(["date", "cea", "cpi" , "t_bill"], axis=1)

Now that I have one data frame I want to reverse the order of the elements. Currently they are in ascending order. I want them in descending order that way when I add my stock data I'll see everything from the most current date to the oldest date.

Milestone 3

In this section I am scraping data from Wikipedia. My goal is to extract the S&P500 table. To accomplish this goal I will use beautiful soup and requests to import the data. I will need to find the right html tags to create the desired table. The issue with source code is they are not always pretty or easy to work with. Challenges that I face are finding the right tags and dealing with missing or incomplete data.

In [18]:
# This code creates a url object.
url = 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%26P_500'
In [19]:
# This code requests data from the website
data = requests.get(url)
In [20]:
# This code extracts the html from wikipedia and displays it.
soup = BeautifulSoup(data.text, 'html.parser')
print(soup.prettify())

             <div class="pie25" style="background:#fc8d59;color:#000; transform: rotate(0.6063turn)" title="Information Technology (30.71%)">

               </a>

         <figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
          <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:1985-_S%26P_500_index_-_percent_changes_by_month.svg">
           <img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="675" data-file-width="1200" decoding="async" height="141" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/1985-_S%26P_500_index_-_percent_changes_by_month.svg/250px-1985-_S%26P_500_index_-_percent_changes_by_month.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/1985-_S%26P_500_index_-_percent_changes_by_month.svg/500px-1985-_S%26P_500_index_-_percent_changes_by_month.svg.png 1.5x" width="250"/>
          </a>
          <figcaption>
           Though there is large variability in month-to-month changes in the S&amp;P 500 index (gray lines), a seasonal pattern emerges when the monthly change values are averaged (bold line).
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-YahooFinance_SPX_5-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-YahooFinance_SPX-5">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             5
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
          <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:S%26P_500_Chart_2025.svg">
           <img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1123" data-file-width="1587" decoding="async" height="177" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/S%26P_500_Chart_2025.svg/250px-S%26P_500_Chart_2025.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/S%26P_500_Chart_2025.svg/500px-S%26P_500_Chart_2025.svg.png 1.5x" width="250"/>
          </a>
          <figcaption>
           S&amp;P 500 Max Min Chart to Jan 2025 with Trend, with plots less Inflation, and comparison plots
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>
          The
          <b>
           Standard and Poor's 500
          </b>
          , or simply the
          <b>
           S&amp;P 500
          </b>
          ,
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-6">
           <a href="#cite_note-6">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            6
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          is a
          <a href="/wiki/Stock_market_index" title="Stock market index">
           stock market index
          </a>
          tracking the stock performance of 500 leading companies listed on
          <a href="/wiki/Stock_exchange" title="Stock exchange">
           stock exchanges
          </a>
          in the
          <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">
           United States
          </a>
          . It is one of the most commonly followed equity indices and includes approximately 80% of the total
          <a href="/wiki/Market_capitalization" title="Market capitalization">
           market capitalization
          </a>
          of U.S. public companies, with an aggregate market cap of more than $49.8 trillion as of March 31, 2025.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sp500r_2-3">
           <a href="#cite_note-sp500r-2">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            2
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
         </p>
         <p>
          The S&amp;P 500 index is a
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Free-float" title="Free-float">
           Free-float
          </a>
          weighted/
          <a href="/wiki/Capitalization-weighted_index" title="Capitalization-weighted index">
           capitalization-weighted index
          </a>
          . As of April 2025, the ten largest companies on the
          <a href="/wiki/List_of_S%26P_500_companies" title="List of S&amp;P 500 companies">
           list of S&amp;P 500 companies
          </a>
          accounted for approximately 35% of the market capitalization of the index and were, in order of highest to lowest weighting:
          <a href="/wiki/Apple_Inc." title="Apple Inc.">
           Apple
          </a>
          (6.4%),
          <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">
           Microsoft
          </a>
          (6.2%),
          <a href="/wiki/Nvidia" title="Nvidia">
           Nvidia
          </a>
          (6.0%),
          <a href="/wiki/Amazon_(company)" title="Amazon (company)">
           Amazon.com
          </a>
          (3.8%),
          <a href="/wiki/Alphabet_Inc." title="Alphabet Inc.">
           Alphabet
          </a>
          (3.6%, including both class A &amp; C shares),
          <a href="/wiki/Meta_Platforms" title="Meta Platforms">
           Meta Platforms
          </a>
          (2.7%),
          <a href="/wiki/Berkshire_Hathaway" title="Berkshire Hathaway">
           Berkshire Hathaway
          </a>
          (2.0%),
          <a href="/wiki/Broadcom" title="Broadcom">
           Broadcom
          </a>
          (1.8%),
          <a href="/wiki/Tesla,_Inc." title="Tesla, Inc.">
           Tesla
          </a>
          (1.6%), and
          <a href="/wiki/JPMorgan_Chase" title="JPMorgan Chase">
           JPMorgan Chase
          </a>
          (1.4%).
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ivv_4-1">
           <a href="#cite_note-ivv-4">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            4
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          The components that have increased their dividends in 25 consecutive years are known as the
          <a href="/wiki/S%26P_500_Dividend_Aristocrats" title="S&amp;P 500 Dividend Aristocrats">
           S&amp;P 500 Dividend Aristocrats
          </a>
          .
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-7">
           <a href="#cite_note-7">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            7
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          Companies in the S&amp;P 500 derive a collective 72% of revenues from the United States and 28% from other countries.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-8">
           <a href="#cite_note-8">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            8
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
         </p>
         <p>
          The index is one of the factors in computation of the
          <a href="/wiki/Conference_Board_Leading_Economic_Index" title="Conference Board Leading Economic Index">
           Conference Board Leading Economic Index
          </a>
          , used to forecast the direction of the economy.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-9">
           <a href="#cite_note-9">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            9
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          The index is associated with many
          <a href="/wiki/Ticker_symbol" title="Ticker symbol">
           ticker symbols
          </a>
          , including ^GSPC,
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-10">
           <a href="#cite_note-10">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            10
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          .INX,
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-11">
           <a href="#cite_note-11">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            11
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          and SPX, depending on market or website.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-12">
           <a href="#cite_note-12">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            12
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
          The S&amp;P 500 is maintained by
          <a href="/wiki/S%26P_Dow_Jones_Indices" title="S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices">
           S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices
          </a>
          , a
          <a href="/wiki/Joint_venture" title="Joint venture">
           joint venture
          </a>
          majority-owned by
          <a href="/wiki/S%26P_Global" title="S&amp;P Global">
           S&amp;P Global
          </a>
          , and its components are selected by a committee.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-S&amp;P500Methodology_3-1">
           <a href="#cite_note-S&amp;P500Methodology-3">
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            3
            <span class="cite-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </a>
          </sup>
         </p>
         <meta property="mw:PageProp/toc">
          <div class="mw-heading mw-heading2">
           <h2 id="Investing_in_the_S&amp;P_500">
            <span id="Investing_in_the_S.26P_500">
            </span>
            Investing in the S&amp;P 500
           </h2>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=S%26P_500&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Investing in the S&amp;P 500">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </div>
          <div class="mw-heading mw-heading3">
           <h3 id="Mutual_and_exchange-traded_funds">
            Mutual and exchange-traded funds
           </h3>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=S%26P_500&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Mutual and exchange-traded funds">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </div>
          <p>
           <a href="/wiki/Index_fund" title="Index fund">
            Index funds
           </a>
           , including
           <a href="/wiki/Mutual_fund" title="Mutual fund">
            mutual funds
           </a>
           and
           <a href="/wiki/Exchange-traded_fund" title="Exchange-traded fund">
            exchange-traded funds
           </a>
           (ETFs), can replicate, before fees and expenses, the performance of the index by holding the same stocks as the index in the same proportions. ETFs that replicate the performance of the index are issued by
           <a href="/wiki/The_Vanguard_Group" title="The Vanguard Group">
            The Vanguard Group
           </a>
           (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:VOO" rel="nofollow">
            VOO
           </a>
           ),
           <a href="/wiki/IShares" title="IShares">
            iShares
           </a>
           (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:IVV" rel="nofollow">
            IVV
           </a>
           ), and
           <a href="/wiki/State_Street_Corporation" title="State Street Corporation">
            State Street Corporation
           </a>
           (
           <a href="/wiki/SPDR_S%26P_500_ETF_Trust" title="SPDR S&amp;P 500 ETF Trust">
            SPDR S&amp;P 500 ETF Trust
           </a>
           ,
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:SPY" rel="nofollow">
            SPY
           </a>
           and
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:SPLG" rel="nofollow">
            SPLG
           </a>
           ). The most liquid based on average daily volume is (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:SPY" rel="nofollow">
            SPY
           </a>
           ), although SPY has a higher annual expense ratio of 0.09% compared to 0.03% for VOO and IVV, and 0.02% for SPLG. Mutual funds that track the index are offered by
           <a href="/wiki/Fidelity_Investments" title="Fidelity Investments">
            Fidelity Investments
           </a>
           ,
           <a href="/wiki/T._Rowe_Price" title="T. Rowe Price">
            T. Rowe Price
           </a>
           , and
           <a href="/wiki/Charles_Schwab_Corporation" title="Charles Schwab Corporation">
            Charles Schwab Corporation
           </a>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-13">
            <a href="#cite_note-13">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             13
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-14">
            <a href="#cite_note-14">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             14
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           <a href="/wiki/Direxion" title="Direxion">
            Direxion
           </a>
           offers
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Leveraged_ETFs" title="Leveraged ETFs">
            leveraged ETFs
           </a>
           which attempt to produce three times the daily return of either investing in (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:SPXL" rel="nofollow">
            SPXL
           </a>
           ) or
           <a href="/wiki/Short_(finance)" title="Short (finance)">
            shorting
           </a>
           (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:SPXS" rel="nofollow">
            SPXS
           </a>
           ) the S&amp;P 500 index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15">
            <a href="#cite_note-15">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             15
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           <a href="/wiki/ProShares" title="ProShares">
            ProShares
           </a>
           offers 2x daily return (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:SSO" rel="nofollow">
            SSO
           </a>
           ) and 3x daily return (
           <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
            NYSE Arca
           </a>
           :
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.nyse.com/quote/ARCX:UPRO" rel="nofollow">
            UPRO
           </a>
           ).
          </p>
          <div class="mw-heading mw-heading3">
           <h3 id="Derivatives">
            Derivatives
           </h3>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=S%26P_500&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Derivatives">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </div>
          <p>
           In the
           <a href="/wiki/Derivative_(finance)" title="Derivative (finance)">
            derivatives
           </a>
           market, the
           <a href="/wiki/Chicago_Mercantile_Exchange" title="Chicago Mercantile Exchange">
            Chicago Mercantile Exchange
           </a>
           (CME) offers
           <a href="/wiki/Futures_contract" title="Futures contract">
            futures contracts
           </a>
           that track the index and trade on the exchange floor in an
           <a href="/wiki/Open_outcry" title="Open outcry">
            open outcry
           </a>
           auction, or on CME's Globex platform, and are the exchange's most popular product. The
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Chicago_Board_Options_Exchange" title="Chicago Board Options Exchange">
            Chicago Board Options Exchange
           </a>
           (CBOE) offers
           <a href="/wiki/Option_(finance)" title="Option (finance)">
            options
           </a>
           on the S&amp;P 500 index as well as on S&amp;P 500 index ETFs, inverse ETFs, and leveraged ETFs.
          </p>
          <div class="mw-heading mw-heading2">
           <h2 id="History">
            History
           </h2>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=S%26P_500&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: History">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </div>
          <p>
           In 1860,
           <a href="/wiki/Henry_Varnum_Poor" title="Henry Varnum Poor">
            Henry Varnum Poor
           </a>
           formed Poor's Publishing, which published an investor's guide to the railroad industry.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-history_16-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-history-16">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             16
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           In 1923, Standard Statistics Company (founded in 1906 as the
           <a href="/wiki/S%26P_Global_Ratings#History" title="S&amp;P Global Ratings">
            Standard Statistics Bureau
           </a>
           ) began rating mortgage bonds
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-history_16-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-history-16">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             16
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           and developed its first stock market index consisting of the stocks of 233 U.S. companies, computed weekly.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           Three years later, it developed a 90-stock index, computed daily.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           In 1941, Poor's Publishing merged with Standard Statistics Company to form
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Standard_%26_Poor%27s" title="Standard &amp; Poor's">
            Standard &amp; Poor's
           </a>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-history_16-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-history-16">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             16
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-17">
            <a href="#cite_note-17">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             17
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           On Monday, March 4, 1957, the index was expanded to its current extent of 500 companies and was renamed the S&amp;P 500 Stock Composite Index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           In 1962, Ultronic Systems became the compiler of the S&amp;P indices including the S&amp;P 500 Stock Composite Index, the 425 Stock Industrial Index, the 50 Stock Utility Index, and the 25 Stock Rail Index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-18">
            <a href="#cite_note-18">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             18
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           On August 31, 1976,
           <a href="/wiki/The_Vanguard_Group" title="The Vanguard Group">
            The Vanguard Group
           </a>
           offered the first
           <a href="/wiki/Mutual_fund" title="Mutual fund">
            mutual fund
           </a>
           to retail investors that tracked the index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-4">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           On April 21, 1982, the
           <a href="/wiki/Chicago_Mercantile_Exchange" title="Chicago Mercantile Exchange">
            Chicago Mercantile Exchange
           </a>
           began trading futures based on the index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-5">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           On July 1, 1983,
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Chicago_Board_Options_Exchange" title="Chicago Board Options Exchange">
            Chicago Board Options Exchange
           </a>
           began trading
           <a href="/wiki/Option_(finance)" title="Option (finance)">
            options
           </a>
           based on the index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-6">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           Beginning in 1986, the index value was updated every 15 seconds, or 1,559 times per trading day, with price updates disseminated by
           <a href="/wiki/Reuters" title="Reuters">
            Reuters
           </a>
           . Prior to this, it had been updated once every minute.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-19">
            <a href="#cite_note-19">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             19
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           On January 22, 1993, the Standard &amp; Poor's Depositary Receipts
           <a href="/wiki/Exchange-traded_fund" title="Exchange-traded fund">
            exchange-traded fund
           </a>
           issued by
           <a href="/wiki/State_Street_Corporation" title="State Street Corporation">
            State Street Corporation
           </a>
           began trading.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-7">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           On September 9, 1997,
           <a href="/wiki/CME_Group" title="CME Group">
            CME Group
           </a>
           introduced the S&amp;P E-mini futures contract.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-keydates_1-8">
            <a href="#cite_note-keydates-1">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             1
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           In 2005, the index transitioned to a public float-adjusted capitalization-weighting.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-20">
            <a href="#cite_note-20">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             20
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           Friday, September 17, 2021, was the final trading date for the original SP big contract which began trading in 1982.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-21">
            <a href="#cite_note-21">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             21
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <div class="mw-heading mw-heading2">
           <h2 id="Selection_criteria">
            Selection criteria
           </h2>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=S%26P_500&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Selection criteria">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </div>
          <p>
           Like other indices managed by
           <a href="/wiki/S%26P_Dow_Jones_Indices" title="S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices">
            S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices
           </a>
           , but unlike indices such as the
           <a href="/wiki/Russell_1000_Index" title="Russell 1000 Index">
            Russell 1000 Index
           </a>
           which are strictly rule-based, the components of the S&amp;P 500 index are selected by a committee. When considering the eligibility of a new addition, the committee assesses the company's merit using the following primary criteria:
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-S&amp;P500Methodology_3-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-S&amp;P500Methodology-3">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             3
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <ol>
           <li>
            <a href="/wiki/Market_capitalization" title="Market capitalization">
             Market capitalization
            </a>
            - Market capitalization must be greater than or equal to US$20.5 billion (effective on January 2, 2025).
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sp20250102_22-0">
             <a href="#cite_note-sp20250102-22">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              22
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
            These market cap eligibility criteria are for addition to an index, not for continued membership. As a result, an index constituent that appears to violate criteria for addition to that index is not removed unless ongoing conditions warrant an index change.
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sp20250102_22-1">
             <a href="#cite_note-sp20250102-22">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              22
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
           </li>
           <li>
            <a href="/wiki/Market_liquidity" title="Market liquidity">
             Market liquidity
            </a>
            and
            <a href="/wiki/Public_float" title="Public float">
             public float
            </a>
            – Annual dollar value traded to float-adjusted market capitalization is greater than 0.75.
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sp20230104_23-0">
             <a href="#cite_note-sp20230104-23">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              23
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
           </li>
           <li>
            <a href="/wiki/Volume_(finance)" title="Volume (finance)">
             Volume
            </a>
            – Minimum monthly trading volume of 250,000 shares in each of the six months leading up to the evaluation date
           </li>
           <li>
            <a href="/wiki/Stock_exchange" title="Stock exchange">
             Stock exchange
            </a>
            – Must be publicly listed on the
            <a href="/wiki/New_York_Stock_Exchange" title="New York Stock Exchange">
             New York Stock Exchange
            </a>
            (including
            <a href="/wiki/NYSE_Arca" title="NYSE Arca">
             NYSE Arca
            </a>
            or
            <a href="/wiki/NYSE_American" title="NYSE American">
             NYSE American
            </a>
            ),
            <a href="/wiki/Nasdaq" title="Nasdaq">
             Nasdaq
            </a>
            (Nasdaq Global Select Market, Nasdaq Select Market or the Nasdaq Capital Market) or
            <a href="/wiki/Cboe_Global_Markets" title="Cboe Global Markets">
             Cboe
            </a>
            (Cboe BZX, Cboe BYX, Cboe EDGA or Cboe EDGX).
           </li>
           <li>
            <a href="/wiki/Domicile_(law)" title="Domicile (law)">
             Domicile
            </a>
            – The company must have its primary listing on a U.S. exchange.
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-24">
             <a href="#cite_note-24">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              24
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
           </li>
           <li>
            Securities that are ineligible for inclusion in the index are
            <a href="/wiki/Limited_partnership" title="Limited partnership">
             limited partnerships
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Master_limited_partnership" title="Master limited partnership">
             master limited partnerships
            </a>
            and their
            <a href="/wiki/Investment_trust" title="Investment trust">
             investment trust
            </a>
            units,
            <a href="/wiki/OTC_Bulletin_Board" title="OTC Bulletin Board">
             OTC Bulletin Board
            </a>
            issues,
            <a href="/wiki/Closed-end_fund" title="Closed-end fund">
             closed-end funds
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Exchange-traded_fund" title="Exchange-traded fund">
             exchange-traded funds
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Exchange-traded_note" title="Exchange-traded note">
             Exchange-traded notes
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Royalty_trust" title="Royalty trust">
             royalty trusts
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Tracking_stock" title="Tracking stock">
             tracking stocks
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Preferred_stock" title="Preferred stock">
             preferred stock
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Unit_trust" title="Unit trust">
             unit trusts
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Warrant_(finance)" title="Warrant (finance)">
             equity warrants
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Convertible_bond" title="Convertible bond">
             convertible bonds
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/Investment_trust" title="Investment trust">
             investment trusts
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="/wiki/American_depositary_receipt" title="American depositary receipt">
             American depositary receipts
            </a>
            , and
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/American_depositary_share" title="American depositary share">
             American depositary shares
            </a>
            .
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-S&amp;P500Methodology_3-3">
             <a href="#cite_note-S&amp;P500Methodology-3">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              3
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
           </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
           A stock may rise in value when it is added to the index since
           <a href="/wiki/Index_fund" title="Index fund">
            index funds
           </a>
           must purchase that stock to continue tracking the index.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-25">
            <a href="#cite_note-25">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             25
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-26">
            <a href="#cite_note-26">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             26
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           A study published by the
           <a href="/wiki/National_Bureau_of_Economic_Research" title="National Bureau of Economic Research">
            National Bureau of Economic Research
           </a>
           in October 2021 alleged that companies' purchases of ratings services from
           <a href="/wiki/S%26P_Global" title="S&amp;P Global">
            S&amp;P Global
           </a>
           appear to improve their chance of entering the S&amp;P 500 index, even if they are not the best fit per the rules.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-27">
            <a href="#cite_note-27">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             27
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-28">
            <a href="#cite_note-28">
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              [
             </span>
             28
             <span class="cite-bracket">
              ]
             </span>
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <div class="mw-heading mw-heading2">
           <h2 id="Performance">
            Performance
           </h2>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=S%26P_500&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Performance">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </div>
          <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1236090951" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style">
           <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
            See also:
            <a href="/wiki/Closing_milestones_of_the_S%26P_500" title="Closing milestones of the S&amp;P 500">
             Closing milestones of the S&amp;P 500
            </a>
            and
            <a href="/wiki/List_of_recessions_in_the_United_States" title="List of recessions in the United States">
             List of recessions in the United States
            </a>
           </div>
           <figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
            <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp">
             <img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="446" data-file-width="1519" decoding="async" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp/500px-S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp/960px-S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp/1000px-S%26P_500_Buybacks_and_Dividends.webp.png 2x" width="500"/>
            </a>
            <figcaption>
             S&amp;P 500 Buybacks and Dividends (quarterly)
             <br/>
             <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r981673959">
              .mw-parser-output .legend{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .legend-color{display:inline-block;min-width:1.25em;height:1.25em;line-height:1.25;margin:1px 0;text-align:center;border:1px solid black;background-color:transparent;color:black}.mw-parser-output .legend-text{}
             </style>
             <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:lightgreen; color:black;">
             </span>
             <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Stock_buyback" title="Stock buyback">
              Stock buyback
             </a>
             <br/>
             <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style">
              <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:green; color:white;">
              </span>
              <a href="/wiki/Dividend" title="Dividend">
               Dividends
              </a>
             </link>
            </figcaption>
           </figure>
           <figure class="mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File">
            <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp" title="S&amp;P 500 annual returns">
             <img alt="S&amp;P 500 annual returns" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1432" data-file-width="4201" decoding="async" height="170" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp/500px-S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp/960px-S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp/1000px-S_%26_P_500_Annual_Returns.webp.png 2x" width="500"/>
            </a>
            <figcaption>
             S&amp;P 500 annual returns
            </figcaption>
           </figure>
           <p>
            Since its inception in 1926, the index's
            <a href="/wiki/Compound_annual_growth_rate" title="Compound annual growth rate">
             compound annual growth rate
            </a>
            —including
            <a href="/wiki/Dividend" title="Dividend">
             dividends
            </a>
            —has been approximately 9.8% (6% after
            <a href="/wiki/Inflation" title="Inflation">
             inflation
            </a>
            ), with the
            <a href="/wiki/Standard_deviation" title="Standard deviation">
             standard deviation
            </a>
            of the return, calculated on a monthly basis, over the same time period being 20.81%. While the index has declined in several years by over 30%,
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-29">
             <a href="#cite_note-29">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              29
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
            it has posted annual increases 70% of the time,
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-love_30-0">
             <a href="#cite_note-love-30">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              30
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
            with 5% of all trading days resulting in record highs.
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-31">
             <a href="#cite_note-31">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              31
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
           </p>
           <p>
            Returns are generally quoted as
            <a href="/wiki/Price_return" title="Price return">
             price returns
            </a>
            (excluding returns from dividends). However, they can also be quoted as
            <a href="/wiki/Total_return" title="Total return">
             total return
            </a>
            , which includes returns from
            <a href="/wiki/Dividend" title="Dividend">
             dividends
            </a>
            and the reinvestment thereof, and "net total return", which reflects the effects of dividend reinvestment after the deduction of
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Withholding_tax" title="Withholding tax">
             withholding tax
            </a>
            .
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sp500r_2-4">
             <a href="#cite_note-sp500r-2">
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               [
              </span>
              2
              <span class="cite-bracket">
               ]
              </span>
             </a>
            </sup>
           </p>

After locating all the data for my analysis, I ran into a snag. I have empty lists in my data and was unable to append it to my empty data frame that I created earlier in the analysis. I tried to find a way to remove the empty lists and was unsuccessful. My solution is to append the list to a csv file and import the file to continue my preprocessing.

In [32]:
# This series of code creates my csv file and imports the data into the file.
csv_file= open('s_p_scrape.csv', 'w')
csv_writer = csv.writer(csv_file)
csv_writer.writerow(['year','change_in_index',  'tot_ann_ret', 'Value_of_1_invested_on_jan_1_1970',
                    '5_years', '10_years', '15_years', '20_years', '25_years'])
for row in column_data[2:]:
    row_data = row.find_all('td')
    
    ind_row_data = [data.text.strip() for data in row_data]
    #print(ind_row_data)
    csv_writer.writerow(ind_row_data)
csv_file.close()

Conclusion

My first data was acquired from the FRED. I utilized three different data sets that I combined into one data frame. To accomplish this, I used a lambda function and joined all data sets on the observation date. After combining the three data sets, I chose to rename the columns and adjusted the date to descending order. The final step was to remove the nan values. Removing the nan values was a good option because I am only interested in the most recent twenty-five years.

My second data set , the S&P, came from Wikipedia. With the S&P I used the beautiful soup and request packages to scrape Wikipedia. When I pulled the HTML from Wikipedia, I needed to isolate the table and extract columns and rows. Once this data was isolated, I needed to construct a data frame to hold the information. This proved to be a problem. When I extracted the data from Wikipedia, I learned the table had empty lists embedded in the data. To solve this, I exported the data to a csv file, removed the empty rows and imported the new file into my program.

The final data source came from FMP Api. This data came in relatively clean. The stock data that I pulled contained the open, close, high, low, and adjusted close data. For my analysis I am only concerned with the adjusted close for each stock. I created a data set that consisted of the adjusted close for the stocks that I pulled from the Api.

The next step is to import all the data sets into a database. I chose to use SQLite3 database. This option satisfied my needs and is a feature of the python program. I created three tables and imported the data into their respective tables. Next, I joined two of the three tables. The S&P data wouldn’t join to the economic indicators and stock data sets. With the combined data sets I created some visualizations. I created five graphs.

The first graph is a histogram of Apple. This graph showed the highest interest when the stock was priced between 160-175. The second graph is a scatter plot that compares two stocks, Apple and Microsoft. This graph shows a positive correlation between the two stocks. In the third graph I constructed a boxplot of the stocks and the economic indicators. The interesting thing about this graph is the lack of outliers. The only stocks with outliers are JP Morgan, Nvidia, and Johnson and Johnson. The fourth graph is a line plot that compares the stocks ad the economic indicators. We saw some expected relationships in the data. The one that was surprising was how JP Morgan closely tracked Apple. In the final graph I created a scatter plot comparing Proctor and Gamble with Johnson and Johnson. There was a relationship, however it wasn’t as strong as I would’ve expected.

In the scope of my analysis I think the biggest ethical concern is misrepresenting data. It is important to never allow personal bias or improper scaling to give improper perceptions regarding the data that I’m using. To avoid this I ensured that any transformations to my data were minimal and didn’t alter the figures that I acquired from the various sources.
